"The sea is ours": Bolivia, a country devoid of coastline, hopes that the court will reopen a path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a rope-covered naval base in La Paz.
Public buildings carry a navy blue flag.
The naval bases of Lake Titicaca for the Amazon bear the motto: "The sea is ours by right.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout Bolivia, a landlocked country, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century is still alive, as is the desire to sail once again in the Pacific Ocean.
Those hopes are perhaps at their highest point in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the International Court of Justice on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, a positive outlook on the outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the pronouncement of the ICJ’s sentence on giant screens scattered across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of their country’s claim, so that, after decades of uncertain negotiations, Chile will be forced to negotiate, granting Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic Bolivian indigenous president, who faces a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has much at stake in Monday’s sentence.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” were the president’s votes last August.
However, some analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will rule in favor of Bolivia, and that little would change even if it did not.
The U.N. body, based in the Netherlands, has no powers to assign Chilean territory to another country and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the ICJ sentence is handed down just six months after hearing the final allegations indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And far from promoting the Bolivian cause, the last four years may have hurt it.
“The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’ belligerent rhetoric has undermined some residual Chilean goodwill, he suggested.
At some point in the future, Bolivia and Chile will continue the talks, but it will be extremely difficult to maintain the dialogue after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making process was unusually fast.
Next Monday will give Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to begin a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “put an end to 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefit,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
"The sentence is an opportunity to understand that we have to overcome the past."
