North Korea says 'not to think' of unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were exacerbating distrust of the United States and that there was no way the country could unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons under the circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as the cessation of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear testing center and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
“However, we do not see any corresponding response from the US,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, there is no way we can disarm ourselves first.”
Although Ri has recycled well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it takes gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in that they do not reject unilateral denuclearization in a first place, in contrast to Pyongyang’s previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearizing the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, opposing until the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream for people who don’t know anything about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of the sanctions is aggravating our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the interested party in this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that steering North Korea’s rockets toward U.S. territory was inevitable after “Bad President” Trump called Kim the “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea's denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a timetable for it, saying “if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously until denuclearization is complete, final and verifiable.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to strangle funding for North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later declared that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, although North Korea later denounced him for “making gangster demands.
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States “takes corresponding measures.”
Pompeo said Kim had told him the “corresponding measures” he was seeking were Trump’s security assurances in Singapore, as well as initiatives to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course that teaches them to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year put all its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat the sexist culture of studying in caffeinated "directs".
One professor concluded that the students of this university at the top of the world rankings often did not have the slightest idea about the most basic concepts about the care they should have with themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
The inspiration for the course came after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, 'Why are you just telling me this in the last year of the course?'
The young woman stated that no one had ever mentioned to her the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance as well as to improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it won’t change students’ behavior instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, just as we all have the right to know the health effects of the choice to smoke,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “making direct” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we get enough sleep with quality should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid getting fat, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in hunger mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical biology and chemistry, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year in his first year at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a campus-wide course, he said.
The next step, according to their expectations, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar program of study before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider using an alarm when going to bed, as well as waking up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can deregulate the circadian rhythm and lead to problems falling asleep.
