Europe is once again victorious after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who has shown to have serious difficulties during most of the tournament, threw the starting tee into the water in hole 16, par 3, giving the victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari has shined in all his rounds, becoming 1 of 4 players to score 5-0-0 since the tournament's current format began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 to the worst-ranked player of the European team, Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
The world's highest-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2-1 to England's Ian Poulter in what may have been his last Ryder Cup appearance.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Spain’s Sergio Garcia became the most awarded European of all tournaments with 25.5 career points.
“It’s not my habit to cry, but today I couldn’t contain myself.
It's been a tough year.
I can't help but thank Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so glad we won the cup.
It was all a team effort and I’m happy to have been able to help,” Garcia said after Europe’s victory.
Pass the word to compatriot Jon Rham who defeated American golf legend Tiger Woods by 2&1 in the singles on Sunday.
"It's impossible to describe the pride I feel for defeating Tiger Woods. I grew up watching him play," said Rahm, 23.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a 13-21-3 Ryder Cup record.
Unusual statistical values of one of the greatest players of all time with 14 great titles won and only beaten by Jack Nicklaus.
With the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau who had a high caliber performance throughout the tournament, the rest of the U.S. national team struggled to make it to the fairway.
U.S. Captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team's disappointing performance. "I'm proud of them. They fought.
This morning, we managed to put some fear in Europe.
We fought.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 players were excellent.
We will reorganize and I will collaborate with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Commission to move forward.
I like a lot of these 12 players and I’m proud to be their captain.
I have to take my hat off to the other team.
They were better."
Red Tide Update: Concentrations Decline in Pinellas, Manatee, and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in Red Tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of less spot proliferation were identified in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Tide spot extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also sighted in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations were recorded near or off the coast of Pinella County, low-to-high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom-to-high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom-to-high concentrations along or off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom-to-medium concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom-to-high concentrations along and off the coast of Le County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritations in northwest Florida.
